3. Prompt 1 — Slow Code Analysis
Prompt used: Explain why this code is slow, identify specific operations causing the slowdown, suggest 2-3 improvements, explain performance concepts, and suggest measurement tools.

Why Is It Slow — Plain English
Imagine you have 5,000 people in a room and you need to introduce every person to every other person. That is 25 million introductions! That is exactly what the nested loops are doing — comparing every product with every other product.

The Three Performance Problems
Problem 1 — Nested Loops (The Main Culprit)
for i in range(len(products)):      # runs 5,000 times
    for j in range(len(products)):  # runs 5,000 x 5,000 = 25 MILLION times
25 million comparisons for just 5,000 products. This is called O(n squared). When products double to 10,000, comparisons quadruple to 100 million!

Problem 2 — Slow Duplicate Checking
if not any(r['product1']['id'] == product2['id'] and
           r['product2']['id'] == product1['id'] for r in results):
Every time a valid pair is found, the code reads through ALL previous results to check for duplicates. As results grows, this search gets slower and slower — like re-reading an entire book every time you want to add one new sentence.

Problem 3 — Generating Then Skipping Self-Comparisons
if i != j:  # skip same product
The code generates all 25 million pairs first, THEN skips ones where a product is compared with itself. Better to never generate them in the first place.

4. Suggested Optimizations
Fix 1 — Start j at i+1 Instead of 0
# SLOW — 25 million comparisons
for i in range(len(products)):
    for j in range(len(products)):
        if i != j:

# FASTER — 12.5 million comparisons, no duplicates possible
for i in range(len(products)):
    for j in range(i + 1, len(products)):
Starting j at i + 1 means: never compares a product with itself, never creates duplicate pairs like (A,B) and (B,A), and cuts comparisons exactly in half.

Fix 2 — Remove the Duplicate Check Entirely
# DELETE THIS — no longer needed with Fix 1
if not any(r['product1']['id'] == product2['id'] and
           r['product2']['id'] == product1['id'] for r in results):
Fix 1 makes duplicates impossible, so this expensive search can be completely removed.

Fix 3 — Two-Pointer Technique (Most Powerful)
# Sort products by price first
sorted_products = sorted(products, key=lambda x: x['price'])
left, right = 0, len(sorted_products) - 1

while left < right:
    combined = sorted_products[left]['price'] + sorted_products[right]['price']
    if abs(combined - target_price) <= price_margin:
        results.append({
            'product1': sorted_products[left],
            'product2': sorted_products[right],
            'combined_price': combined,
            'price_difference': abs(target_price - combined)
        })
        left += 1
    elif combined < target_price - price_margin:
        left += 1
    else:
        right -= 1
Instead of comparing every pair, two pointers move toward each other intelligently. Reduces 25 million comparisons to roughly 5,000 — almost instant!

